</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Common. Revised for the region by 
<bibRefCitation author="Paretas-Martinez, J" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" pagination="207 - 214" title="Description of four new species of Dilyta from the Afrotropical region." url="10.4001/003.017.0211" volume="17" year="2009">Paretas-Martinez et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Mostly tiny and dark brown charipines. Separated from 
<taxonomicName authority="Fergusson, 1986" authorityName="Fergusson" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Apocharips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apocharips" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Apocharips</taxonomicName>
by lacking lateral ridges on scutellum, having at most a small posterior ridge, and by usually having T2 discernable as a separate sclerite. May be confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Alloxysta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloxysta</taxonomicName>
, but has an oval-rounded metasoma covered in the major part by a syntergite (no posterior tergites visible) and has the two apical articles of the female antenna immovable conjoined. Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Alloxysta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloxysta</taxonomicName>
are usually larger, paler, has more pubescence, and have a more smoothly convex mesoscutum; 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Dilyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilyta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilyta</taxonomicName>
have a characteristic anterior hump in lateral view.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Figure 15. 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Dilyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilyta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilyta</taxonomicName>
species (Madagascar). A habitus lateral view B head and mesosoma dorso-lateral view C scutellum, posterio-dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Holarctic and Old World Tropics. Afrotropical records: Cameroon (
<bibRefCitation author="Lebel, TJ" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Agronomy" pageId="154" pageNumber="155" pagination="37 - 44" title="Parasitism of Mesohomotomatessmanni Aulmann (Psylloidea, Carsidaridae) Psyllid Pest of Theobromacacao and Octolobusspectabilis (Sterculiaceae) in Cameroon and Taxonomy of Parasitoids." url="10.3923/ja.2007.37.44" volume="6" year="2007">Lebel and Modesta 2007</bibRefCitation>
), Democratic Republic of Congo (
<bibRefCitation author="Benoit, PLG" journalOrPublisher="Revue de Zoologie et de Botanique Africaines" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="437 - 440" title="Deux Cynipidae-Charipinae inédits du Congo Belge." volume="53" year="1956 e">Benoit 1956e</bibRefCitation>
), Botswana, Ghana, Kenya, Somalia, South Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Paretas-Martinez, J" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" pagination="207 - 214" title="Description of four new species of Dilyta from the Afrotropical region." url="10.4001/003.017.0211" volume="17" year="2009">Paretas-Martinez et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
), Madagascar (
<bibRefCitation author="Pujade-Villar, J" journalOrPublisher="Orsis" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" pagination="135 - 140" title="First records of genus Dilyta from Madagascar with description of Dilytaparetasmartinezi n. sp. (Hymenoptera: Cynipoidea: Figitidae: Charipinae)." url="10.3897/zookeys.168.2030" volume="26" year="2012">Pujade-Villar and Ferrer-Suay 2012</bibRefCitation>
), Rwanda, Zimbabwe (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferrer-Suay, M" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="255 - 266" title="A review of Alloxysta species (Hymenoptera: Cynipoidea: Figitidae: Charipinae) from Africa." url="10.4001/003.021.0222" volume="21" year="2013">Ferrer-Suay et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
), Central African Republic, Nigeria, Tanzania, Uganda, Yemen (here).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<pageBreakToken pageId="44" pageNumber="45" start="start">Biology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Hyperparasitoids attacking encyrtid wasps on psyllids (
<bibRefCitation author="Menke, AS" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="155" pageNumber="156" pagination="136 - 158" title="North American Charipidae, key to genera, nomenclature, species checklist and a new species of Dilyta Foerster (Hymenoptera, Cynipoidea)." volume="93" year="1991">Menke and Evenhuis 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
